AAR CY 2018, Part II, No. 1 | Properties of the Municipality of Culaba reported at P117 million as of December 31, 2019 under Property Plant and Equipment (PPE) continued to be unsubstantiated, not fully accounted and exposed to possible loss or misuse due to laxity in recording, reporting and maintaining ledgers by the Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer, contrary to pertinent laws, rules and regulations, resulting in unreliable balance of the accounts under PPE. | We reiterate our previous recommendations that the Municipal Mayor constitute immediately an Inventory Committee who shall perform and complete the following tasks before the end of CY 2020: 

Conduct physical count of LGU properties and mark counted assets with Property Tags; 



prepare the RPCPPE with complete details; 

submit the RPCPPE to the Municipal Accountant who shall reconcile the same with her records, and;


locate the missing properties of the LGU and submit a report thereon for appropriate legal action on the persons responsible for its loss. 

We further recommend that the Municipal Accountant:

Coordinate with the Property Officer and the Municipal Engineer to identify and prepare the list of assets under the Water Supply System account which were transferred to Culaba Water District, confirm the nature of such transfer and disclose the same in the Notes to FS;

Record all procurement as well as payments of on-going and completed infrastructure projects in the appropriate accounts as prescribed in the PPSAS  Revised Chart of Accounts;
Record the tractor donated to the LGU by DA RFO8 in the Agricultural and Forestry Equipment account;

Deduct at all times the required 10% Retention money on every progress billing of contractors and record the amount deducted in the Construction In-Progress account with corresponding entry to Guaranty/Security Deposit Payable account;

Record all road networks projects in the books pertaining to projects prior to CY 2015 and derecognize the carrying value of projects which has undergone re-blocking or repairs;

Prepare the accounting entry to transfer from the books of the Municipality the cost of completed barangay projects to the books of the recipient Barangay;


Review and sign each JEV prepared by the accounting staff;

Maintain complete General Ledgers, Subsidiary Ledgers, PPE Ledger Cards, Real Property Ledger Cards; and


Prepare the complete and accurate data in the Financial Statements per Fund to support the consolidated FS.

We also recommend that the Designated Property Officer prepare and maintain the following:

Property Cards for all assets of the LGU based on the RPCPPE and every time there are new procured assets;

Issue the Inventory Custodian Slips (ICS) for supplies issued and the Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) for equipment issued to all employees who are custodians of LGU assets;

Renew PAR every three years to validate the persons accountable;


record all donated assets, including the donated ambulance van based on the fair market value, if no document is available as to its cost or obtain documents from the donor agency to obtain its acquisition cost;

The Municipal Assessor obtain and complete the documentary requirements for the transfer of ownership of lots purchase by, or donated to, the LGU;

Provide adequate storage for unserviceable equipment; and


Request for disposal of unserviceable properties.

AAR CY 2019, Part II, No. 8 | Additional income from different sources could have been earned by the LGU had the Municipal Revenue Code of 2007 been revised to impose more realistic rates on the taxpayers, in accordance with Section 191 of Republic Act No. 7160 thus, revenues from market stalls were not maximized.  Also, lease contracts signed in 2018 providing for free rental for 10 years from lessees of 15 market stallholders were not amended even if the same was disadvantageous to the LGU, thus, the Municipality was deprived of the funds that could be used for its regular operations. | We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Constitute a Local Finance Committee who shall review the Municipal Revenue Code of 2007 and prepare a list of revisions adopting an updated and realistic rates to be collected from its revenue-generating properties;

Submit to the Sangguniang Bayan immediately the proposed revisions on the Municipal Revenue Code for the issuance of the appropriate Ordinance;

Renew all contracts with market stallholders including other areas for rent and revise the Contract of Lease Agreements to incorporate the latest revised approved rates and delete provisions which are unfavorable to the LGU. 

We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:

conduct an inspection and inventory of all stalls for rent by the Municipality;

prepare a list thereof with the names of the lessees of each stall;

submit said list to the Municipal Mayor as input in the renewal of Contract; and

 enforce payment of the unpaid rent from CY 2018 to CY 2019.

AAR CY 2019,
Part II, No.14 | 14. Job Order personnel hired by LGU Culaba were paid wages below the daily minimum rate and even without accomplishment reports to confirm actual works done, contrary to RTWPB Wage Order No. RB VIII-20 and 21 and Section 4 of PD 1445, thus JOs were deprived of benefits due them while payments were of doubtful validity. | We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:



pay the mandated daily minimum wage prescribed by the RTWPB for Region VIII; 


55) reduce the number of Job Order personnel in the LGU to those which are considered essential and urgent; 

56) revise the Contract of Service of Job Order personnel to include information on their specific duties, assigned areas, rates, period covered by the contract, address, with pictures and signed as acknowledgement by the JO being hired; 

57) require all JOs, prior to payment of wages, to submit an accomplishment report, duly filled-up and validated by the LGU official who is the JO’s immediate supervisory; and

58) compel the Accountant and Treasurer to pay JO wages only when the payroll is duly supported with Contracts (initial payment) and Accomplishment Reports signed by Heads of Offices where they are assigned.

